I saw the tall alien wolf posted in the other thread and didn't get the chance to mention
Earth has effectively the highest possible gravity a planet can have, and still allow for space travel. In biological terms, everything here will be stronger than any equivalently structured alien species, and we will also be much shorter.
Odds are that when we find alien life, they will be incredibly tall, but still lightweight.
To make things even better, sexual dimorphism developed the way it did due to it being the most efficient. Early on in evolutionary development, the entire species is less likely to succumb to a genetic disease if it varies it's genetic pattern between more than one parent. Too many parents however, results in terrible inefficiency, and this reproduction is less likely.
The odds of us finding tall sexy aliens that are male and female is greater than us finding little gray goblins who want to bomb us to death.

Anonymous Wed 15 Nov 2023 06:50:53 No.61132529 Report
Quoted By: >>61133081 >>61133459 >>61133697 >>61136686
>>61131234
I like Dakota BECAUSE he's such an asshole. He is radically different from most mc's I've read on here. I remember when Underneath the Armor first dropped someone complained that Anon was such a chad with his muscles and fighting ability that he couldn't relate to him. Another poster rightly pointed out that Anon wasn't a Chad, he was just autistic about his sport.
Dakota on the other hand is clearly written to be a Chad of sorts: He's in peak physical condition, he's cocky and self-confident to an degree approaching a mental disorder, and he has no problems getting pussy. Whenever I read CTASO I get the feeling Jacklin read one too many stories about a down on his luck Anon getting a Waifur who will play vidya with him, and just snapped and wrote the polar opposite.
I also like the way Dakota is written because
other characters do not reinforce that he's cool and awesome. They acknowledge his talents but find him irritating and grating. DeeDee, the main love interest, even has to come to grips with the fact that her liking him means she probably has an awful taste in men. That she is the type of girl to fall for a "bad boy". When bad writers attempt this type of character they often turn him into a Gary Stu and have everyone around him drops to their knee in worship. But here, everyone merely tolerates Dakota.
>>61131405
But I have to acknowledge that Jacklin really is walking a tight rope with this story. One bad chapter can really spoil the whole thing at this point. The problem here is that the reader needs to meet Jacklin halfway, they have to put up with Dakota for a while before getting used to him, and its very jarring. Something is building up, the "Greek Chorus" as this Anon says. And it all needs to be for the purpose of something big, something on the scale of his better known stories that have very strong reputations here. I reckon those are hard standards to keep, even for him.
Pic related.
